This is my first annotation here on GK.  This particular game was a lot of fun...  a Kieseritsky gambit a poisoned pawn and a pretty checkmate (well pretty for us  hanging around 1450!)  Enjoy...

As white I'm a fan of e4.
Standard reply.
The King's Gambit leads to many sharp lines.
Accepting the gambit is generally considered to be the best reply.
Defending the pawn but weakening the kingside.
And we've arrived at the classic position of the Kieseritsky gambit where White threatens to win back the lost pawn.
!?  Interesting.  Black doesn't accept the loss of the pawn and sends the brave soldier to the sixth rank to put pressure on f2.  I'm going to have to be careful not to allow him to exploit it.
Taking control of the center and threatening to win the pawn at f4.
?!  Huh?  I would have expected Black to play ..d6 to drive off the knight or ..d5 to fight for the center.  Instead he brings out his queen to threaten my knight which has a defender...
... and now has two.  I can now win the pawn at g3 at my leisure.

Ahhhhh!  So THAT'S what her majesty decided to come out and play for!  Black has my b2 pawn caught undefended and has an eye out for more-- indeed after Qxb2 my rook is trapped and helpless.  But I had a sense at this point that if Black DID gobble my pawn I would actually be in a stronger position!

Freeing and defending the rook.  Take a look at the position.  White has 3 pieces out including a centralized knight while Black has only the lonely queen out pawn-hunting.  Still good defense might have salvaged the game at least for a little while...
... but instead Black goes for the undefended b-pawn.  OM NOM NOM NOM
Defends the knight.  I can now win the queen with Nc4!
Qa3 serves the same purpose.  Time for her majesty to get outta Dodge...
!  Ouch.  "Your majesty you don't look well.  Perhaps it was that poisoned pawn  you ate?"
The only safe square.
"Hey fork you man!"
Mmm rookalicious.

?  Wait you're down in material and you want to offer an exchange that gives me a check?!  Weird... though I can SORTA see the logic behind it he attacks d4 and if I did exchange he would threaten e4...
... so I kill two birds with one stone and add a defender to each.
Okay you REALLY want to exchange huh?
I've got e4 covered for now but I haven't castled yet and I'm feeling a little exposed in the middle.  Still I probably shouldn't be complaining given how well everything else is going!
Take back the Knight!
Or maybe not.  (If Bxa8 Rb8 ! and utter nastiness to follow.)

??  I think Black was (understandably!) in panic mode at this point.  He was afraid of the pin on his queen by Bg5... except I had no intention of playing that as it could be parried by f6 or Nf6.  A wasted move.
And now my center is freed with the e4 pawn unpinned!
Better late than never.
Closing the center and blocking the development of the knight... poor guy has no squares to move to!  And to make matters worse if.. dxe5 dxe5 with a discovered check!
Still with an eye to reclaim the knight.  But the Black king is just inching closer to doom!
Run your majesty run!
Qd8 was more precise.
Escape!  And Black is now officially screwed.  After this move I did some analysis and found mate in 6 possibly a couple more if Black used his queen to eliminate an attacker.
At least the knight can finally move.
!  BOOOOOM!  A battering ram knocks down the front door!
Virtually forced.
Defended by TWO pieces (because one is never enough!  Okay sometimes it is.  Shush.) my queen forces Black's king to b8 where he's trapped!
Now all I have to do is put him in check.
I knew I'd get around to castling eventually just didn't think it'd be the second-to-last move of the game!  (If the knight hadn't moved I'd play Kd2 because of complications arising with Bxd4  etc.)
Nd5 was his only hope but it would only be prolonging the inevitable.  (if ..Nd5 24. Rb1  Nb6 25. Rxb6  axb6 26. Qa8#)
And checkmate!  I hope you were both amused and informed by this annotation... thanks to pstultz for the game!
This is a game played in as you can see dave1973's mini-tournament (in which I am also playing!) which at the time of annotating is still in progress.
The Queen's Gambit - my favourite opening. In itself this is not a gambit as White can force the pawn's recapture with 3.Qa4  and 4.Qxc4 but this continuation is useless and rarely played.
The Slav Defence a solid line for Black.
This is the usual move in many lines of the Queen's Gambit Declined.
I don't like this move. Far better to play 4.e4 and build up a strong pawn centre. 4.e3 is too passive and blocks in the dark-squared bishop.
The early emergence of a queen on the queenside is relatively common in the Queen's Gambit.

As is seen here one of the factors that White must contend with after the Queen's Gambit Accepted is Black building up massive control over the queenside wing often pushing pawns far into White's territory.

Black wants to try attacking on the other side. I personally would have preferred keeping the queen where it was and developing more pieces - as you can see Black has developed absolutely no minor pieces.
Black will pay for his lag in development - White is building up control of the centre.
I would have gone for 9.e5 pushing Black's only developed piecs back. However 9.Qc2 is a good move to shore up the queenside.
Black walked straight into that fork.
Just look at White's superb control. His bishops are powering down on Black's king locking him into the centre.
Black controls the open file pressurising White's king in return.

I would have preferred 14...Qg4 trying to force a way into Black's kingside and if 15.g3 then 15...Qh3 severely threatening and trapping White's queen and then maybe a sacrifice ...Bxg3 or bringing the bishops into the attack in some other way. This could possibly have been a winning attack for Black!
Black has just wasted two moves.
White is threatening a checkmate on Black's poor exposed King - this should teach Black never to leave the King in the centre!
Black's lack of development makes White's breaking into Black's position easy.
A queen sacrifice finishes Black off...

...WHAM! Checkmate. Note that this would not have been so easy for White if Black had developed his minor pieces sooner and castled as soon as possible...which in turn means he should not have been wasting moves messing around with his queen so early and so much.

"Wham!" the King pawn came down with a thud I was amazed at the force with which Fischer slammed the king pawn down.
I looked at Fischer and saw pure hatred staring back at me.  I thought this must be what Jack the Rippers victims must have seen.  After that I concentrated on the board and didn't look at Fischer.

this is not quite as bad as it looks with the proper follow up.  Still e6 has to be the best move.  e6 takes the pressure off f7 for a while.  White often follows up with f2-f4-f5 and Black has to choose between ...exf5 or  ...e5 either of which opens things up for the Sozin bishop.  Also there are tactics based on Nd5 exd5 Bxd5 to look out for.
Wow I thought Fischer has overlooked something.  I am going to win a pawn.  7...Nxe4 8 Nxe4 Bxf5 and I am a pawn up.

At this point Fischer actually took about 15 seconds to look something over.  All his prior moves had been made instantly.  It took him about 2 minutes to make the rounds.  Which was a fair amount of time to think about your move but less than I thought I would have.   Now I had figure out how to defend my d-pawn.
This was the only way I could figure out to defend the pawn.  I felt slightly sick as I realized all my pieces were on their original squares.
Now I needed to defend against the mate threat.  I did see that Qd7 would lose to Nf6 check.  That left Queen to e7 or c7.

This game was in fact played in Division A3 the 3rd highest division of Gameknot's chess league - it seems as though this game is bound to be interesting!
The main line of the Sicilian Defence.
This move leads to the Sicilian Najdorf a variation of the Sicilian with seemingly endless possibilities.

Black now has a solid position with space for development on the queenside and a well-defended kingside to castle into. Note his well-placed bishops. White has a more open position also well-developed and is aiming to open up the centre develop a bishop and prepare a semi-open file for his kingside rook after castling with 8.f4.
Black moves his queen onto the c7-square controlling the open queenside; White castles kingside to develop his rook onto the soon-to-be-open f-file.
A good move. White takes advantage of Black's closed position and tries to block it up. This also allows White's bishop to enter the action.
Both sides swing their bishops into play.
I'm not so sure about this move. I see no point in it. Does anyone else?
White clearly has his bishops positioned very well controlling many crucial diagonals. As for Black's dark-squared bishop...

White looks as though he is clearly aiming to attack Black's kingside: perhaps he is aiming for Qg3 Bxh6 and Qxg7  . Black's queen is far away Black's minor pieces will clearly have trouble mobilising to defend and ...g6 with only lead to more trouble after fxg6. I think this would have won White the game!
I can see no reason why white did not attack.
Both sides are using the open queenside to try to win material and/or push a pawn.
Black is effectively mobilising his knight to harrass White's queen and try to open up the queenside for his formidable rooks.

Success! Black has cleared away White's control over the queenside and made large acquisitions of space in White's side of the board. ...Ra7 looks like a good option to completely gain control of the a-file and make White's king vulnerable along the 1-rank.
This is not a useful move. White's king should be entering the endgame to fight for his pawns not hiding in the corner where he will do nothing and be even more vulnerable.

Starting with e4 gives black a lot of options but almost all lead to dynamic exciting games.
There is a lot of variety in the Ruy Lopez.  Peterliberty enjoys competing in the exciting world of the unknown.
Black chooses the unexpected exd4.  The pin is relieved with b5 and should precede the d-pawn capture.
White passes the chance to capture the knight and force black to double pawns on the c-file.
A series of simplifying exchanges begins.
This game is showing no signs of lasting 102 moves.
Is an advance on the Queen-side coming?
Or will it be an attack on the King-side?
Black is choosing to apply pressure on the King-side.  Black's counter attack will be unsuccessful because white holds an advantage in the center.
This forces another exchange of pieces in which black will lose a piece.
Black is now at a material disadvantage and is facing the problem of a rook on the 7th rank.

White needs to move the King forward in its own defense.  The move allows the tide to turn in black's direction.  Black will soon be causing serious problems for white with his King-side pawn advantage.
White will win the game on the Queen-side but first must stop the King-side threat.
Black is now in White's rear.  Even though White has a preponderance of force Black has the advantage of pressure from the front and the rear.
The Knight will be working hard for the remainder of the game.  There's still no sign this game will last 102 moves.
The white King must remain on the King-side in defense of that flank while the black-King takes over in the center.
This move puts black in a very good position and nearly takes the white rook out of the game.
White fears Rc2 .  But the black King is moving into the battle and the Knight will have to do most of the fighting.  White is very uncomfortable right now.
This prepares for an advance of the c-Pawn a move which will improve white's chances considerably.

White's problem here is stopping the black Pawns.  The King-side Pawn is lost leaving black with two connected King-side Pawns (or two isolated pawns) and King right in the middle of them.  It is not looking good for white.
White lures the black Rook into capturing the c-Pawn.  Once the black Rook leaves the 2nd rank the white Rook will be able to depart the a-file and become more involved in the action.
Black takes the bait.  Now perhaps white will find a way to stop the King-side attack.
White plans to move the Rook to b3 and advance the pawn to a4 then return to a3 where the Rook will guard the pawn's romp to a8.
White should probably proceed with his plan here.
White decides to first encourage black's forces into a dispersed rather than a coordinated pattern.
After 55. . .  Rxc3 56.Nxc3 Kd4 57.a4 the black King cannot take the knight because the a-Pawn runs to the Queening square.  He cannot defend the pawns either because the a-Pawn is free.
Black wisely declines the exchange.
The white Pawn begins its long march to the 8th rank.  Now the game is definitely showing signs of a long struggle.
White now stands better and the threat on the King-side has all but dissipated.

White believes he can win with the Knight Pawn and King.  They can now be coordinated.  Eventually the Knight will have to land on c7 providing either checkmate with the Pawn on a7 or preventing the King from going to a8 and either obtaining a stalemate with no place to move or blocking the a-Pawn from promotion.  The Pawn may never reach promotion but will be the key to winning the game.
Black declines the exchange and is now fighting for a draw in the most advantageous way possible by eliminating white's forces with a timely exchange.
White continues the march of the foot soldier and black is forced to make generally meaningless moves in the hope that white will open the door for a draw.
White was hoping to land the Knight on the crucial c7 square but the black Rook keeps getting in the way.  Oh well if White takes care to avoid a draw he should be able to win.
White cannot advance the Pawn to a7 forcing the King to a8 yet because a forced exchange of the Rooks would end in a draw.
Now we are there.  100. . .  Rxb7 101.axb7  Kb8 102.Nc6
Black declines the exchange of Rooks but it makes no difference.
Whatever move black makes now with his Rook the game will end with either Rb8   or Ra7

The game begins with a King pawn opening where tactics can develop quickly for both sides.
Black chooses a Sicilian an opening that provides the most fight to the move [1.e4].
This is the mainline of the Sicilian Opening.
This has been a preference of mine lately. I like the center control provided by the knight and it also provides a shield against a future [Bf1-b5].

This is a variation of the Sicilian of which I do not know the name. I would call it a 3.Bc4 Sicilian. To me it looks like it will turn to an open Sicilian where the center opens up through pawn exchanges.

I choose a Paulsen pawn formation which has served me well against this type of opening. The text move has the advantage of blocking the bishop pressure at f7 and controlling d5 so that the b1 knight can not be developed there later.

The text move is not good for white because it provides no benefits but it does weaken the pawn structure king-side. A better idea is to play [4.0-0] instead which if played then there is no worry about black playing [4...Qg5] to attack the g2 pawn. Normally the pawn is defended while the bishop remains at f1 but since the bishop has been committed to c4 protection of the g2 pawn must be considered. Notice how moving the g pawn also affects the knight at f3 which now must be protected which keeps the queen tied to this duty which takes away queen mobility.

This is a move I tend to play against the bishop in this opening. The obvious idea is to exchange by NxB to obtain the bishop advantage (having both bishops while the opponent does not). A small positional advantage can be obtained if white plays [5.Be2] due to the cramped position for white and a tempo is gained because after the bishop retreat it is black who plays with the initiative - which allows black another move towards catching up in development.
Supporting the bishop but allowing the exchange.
Black gains the bishop advantage with this move and will seek to exchange pawns later so the bishops can become more active.
This pawn formation creates a sort of bind for black who has to work to remove the bind at some point.

This move serves many purposes: to keep the knight from developing to e5 to allow [...Ng8-f6] by protecting against [e4-e5] to protect the c5 pawn and to obtain a little more space. The d7 pawn when left in place can be constrictive and may allow some successful knight attacks by white.
Now white just needs to develop 3 pieces from the back rank (QBN) for complete development. Black needs to develop (0-0NBQB) and so must make each move count for the following moves.
The text move is played to prevent the immediate [8.Bg5] which if played next would lose a piece for white [8.Bg5 Bxg5  9.Nxg5 Qxg5  10.Qxd6 Qe7]. So white must choose another move.
A good developing move.

Now [9.Bg5] is possible without losing a piece but the text move is necessary so that black can castle and complete development. Black by playing the order bishop then knight is able to castle first without having to deal with any possible [BxN] exchange. Note that developing the bishop before knight is possible only because white can not play [Qd1-g4] to attack the g7 pawn - due to the knight blocking the queen line.

An attacking move which does not look bad because after [9...dxe5  10.Nxe5] there is some pressure on the black position. The downside of this move is that after an exchange some central control is given up by white.
Notice there is no danger in a queen exchange for black because the queen is guarded by the bishop.

Black continues the plan for development. The position is about equal with the difference of the open pawn structure for the white castle. Its not something that can be taken advantage of easily by black after the queen exchange so white is okay.

Before the queen exchange material was even from a point count but every exchange should start to favor black eventually because of having the bishop advantage. Better was [11.Qe2] to move the queen off the back rank and continue development and to control the squares (e4g4) to keep them from the f6 knight.

Notice that the result of the exchange is that black has a strong positional plus of having the only rook that is on an open file. This is something to keep in mind when calculating an exchange - where do the pieces end up afterwards. The position is not open enough for black to obtain the best use of the bishops so white still has some chances to use the knights which work best against bishops when there are more pawns on the board.
The text move puts pressure on c5. The move [12.Bf4?] loses tempo from [12...Nh5].

The text move offers a knight exchange which will remove the pressure from the e5 knight. White must choose to exchange or retreat the knight. A benefit of retreat is that 2 knights can be stronger than just a knight and bishop. This is a consideration when playing against 2 bishops. This is a generalized reason but it could be a favorable choice for white in the long term.
Perhaps better is [13.Nd3] which applies more pressure to c5 and blocks the file from the d8 rook.

The text is an awkward development of the bishop but is necessary to tie the rooks. and it has an idea behind it of developing the bishop to c6 where it best developed for control of the a8-h1 diagonal. At this point in the game my strategy was to find the best placement of my pieces and the bishop looks good on the a8-h1 diagonal especially considering the pawn structure of the white castle.

This move is not the best. Notice for white how the pawns are on the same color as the bishop? This takes away mobility of the bishop which makes it less useful.  A bishop that can not move becomes a bad bishop. Perhaps better would be to use the pawn majority on the queen-side to create a pawn storm. A goal would be to seek an exchange of a pawn from the c file so the pawns will not be doubled and also if possible try to get a pawn promotion in the end. Lately I have started looking at the board from a pawn point of view where you can play in the center king-side or queen-side. You can look for play in one of those areas or sometimes in two of them. Typically you use the pawns on the opposite side of the board from where you castled because they are not guarding the king.

It is good to use the pawns on the queen-side but maybe better is to first move the knight from where it blocks the c2 pawn. Then the pawn advance [c2-c3] will support [b2-b4] to entice an exchange of [...cxb4] so the c pawn is undoubled by [cxb4]. And if black notices the plan and plays [...a7-a5] then there is the move [a2-a3] and white will be successful in the exchanges.
Black seeks to make the rooks more useful by doubling them up on the d file. When there are no tactical or attacking moves available then it is good to make moves that strengthen your position.

An interesting formation has formed where the queen-side pawns work against blacks white squared bishop and the pawns king-side work against blacks black squared bishop. The white queen-side pawns are now mostly without mobility. It appears that white has no attacking ideas and it is hard to suggest attacking ideas in this position. The placement of each piece in the opening makes a big difference in the quality of your middle and end game - so it is good to have a middle/end-game plan for each opening that you like to play.
This move prevents [Nc3-b5] and is made to make the opponents knight less useful.
This move creates a backwards pawn at g3 which can be a problem if a rook is placed on the g file. Of course the g pawn is safe for the moment.
Continuing the plan of doubling the rooks. Notice how the prior move by black prevents the knight from gaining access to the a7 square - where it would attack the c6 bishop.

Seeking to open up the position and bring the rook into the attack of c5. Not the best move because of the tactic that black has available of [18...Bf6!] which loses the knight or rook. Better is [18.Ra1-d1] where the rook is backed up by the f1 rook and the knight. If the knight is later attacked by [18...Bf6] then [19.Rxd7 Rxd7  20.Ne2] and the knight is safe.
Black creates a counter-attack which keeps the pawn at c5 safe due to the attack on the c3 knight. Notice the pin on the knight prevents it from moving without losing the rook.
This is the best method to lose material because the alternative [19.Rd1 Bxc3] is -3 pts and the text move [19.Ne2 Bxa1  20.Rxa1] results in -2 pts and allows a piece recapture.

A quick positional assessment shows that there are bishops of opposite colors which means that there is some potential for reaching a draw typically. But the material difference will make that less likely. White has a pawn majority queen-side and black does on the king-side. Both players should try to centralize the king usually but in this game the 2 rooks will make that difficult for white. A strategy for white may be to try and create a fortress on the queen-side for the king after exchanging pawns king-side. For black the best strategy is to make the most of the rooks perhaps by [...Rd1 ] to exchange rooks for a greater advantage.
The end result of the strategy is that black has a rook on the 8th rank where it can attack the queen-side pawns.
Protecting c5.
A good move (!) that prevents the rook from getting behind the pawns. Nicely done!
The rook has nothing more to attack and moves to a better position. Note that [23...Rd6] is met with [24.Bf4]. The text move appears the best choice.
Its an attack but does not gain an advantage due to [24...f6] and it loses the f5 pawn. Better was [24.fxe6].
Taking advantage of the tempo gained - black captures the pawn before [fxe6] can be played.
A risky move which attempts to make doubled black pawns by [26...cxb4]. It has the unfortunate aspect of hanging the a4 pawn.
The text move (?) is not the best choice. Better was [26...Bxa4].
A good move (!) - 2 pawns for the price of one because of the bishop at e3.
Unfortunately for white the hanging a4 pawn loses some of the advantage of the pawn exchanges.
For safety of the pawn.
Now there is an unfortunate position for white where there are 3 hanging pieces lined up in a file. This is taken advantage of by the rook.
A good try but this move enables black to create two attacks. Better was [30.Bd4].
Good counter-play (!). Always try to use it.
Black is okay with losing the bishop because the material advantage becomes stronger by exchanges.
The rest of the game is played using the rook advantage with the idea of promoting the a6 pawn.

The check on the next move is allowed by black with the idea of pushing the pawn to promotion. The king will be able to move to safety and there are no forks or secondary moves that will cause problems afterwards.

Moving towards the center. Also possible was [35...Kf8] where it takes 3 knight jumps to check the king. The text move is better because the king will be centralized for more board control. When playing against knights there are certain squares you can use to your advantage. Like in this position observe the squares (c6d7d5e6) require 2 knight moves to attack these squares and the squares (c7c5e7e5) require 1 knight move to be attacked and also note the safest squares (b8b4f8f4) which takes 3 knight moves to be attacked. If you look at the square colors relative to the knight you can see how most black squares can be attacked in 1 move and most white squares in 2 moves.
Attacking the rook.

The alternative move [36...Rc2 ] is not so good because the king can begin to maneuver towards the rook which will cause it to have to move to remain safe. The text move is best because the rook is far enough from king and knight attacks. Note that the idea is to use the rook to prevent the king from reaching the pawn on the a file. White could try to use the knight as a shield to step past the rook but it would take some time.
Its hard to get at the pawn due to the rook placement and because an outside passed pawn is a difficult target for a knight.
Hoping to blockade the pawn at a3 or maybe exchange the knight for pawn later to prevent the pawn promotion.
The rook attacks with the idea of forcing the knight away and then the pawn can continue the journey.
The knight blockades the pawn but unfortunately there is no support and the rook will be able to chase it again.
A good try in the circumstance.
Chasing the knight to gain the a3 square.
Now the pawn can go a bit further.
It looks like black will lose either rook or pawn but there is an intermezzo (an in-between move) which will allow both to be kept.
The text move (!) gives black the opportunity to move the rook and the pawn to safety.
There are no saving moves for white.

Black Resigned. The most important themes in this game were piece safety tactics calculation B vs N good piece placement pawn structures open files square control. Getting better at chess is like a roller coaster ride. While you are learning you tend to focus on certain aspects of the game while losing sight of other aspects - which is normal. Its good to try and improve each area to its fullest and you will find yourself collecting stronger attributes for your play.

I look back at some of the illustrative games in the World Database and find that the move e5 was played to exchange the central pawns - white drew that game so I thought it was a reasonable plan here.  Maybe a better idea would have been to have played either Bc2 or b3 here at least the former would have avoided what is to come.  I now have a tip for all beginners and intermediate players here - when you come to the end of the database do check to see what is covering what and then decide on what piece to move in order to improve your position especially for overloads like this one otherwise you will worsen it.

Thus begins a very interesting game played on Gameknot.
Main line King Pawn.

The Spanish opening/Ruy Lopez. White has his sights fixed on Black's e-pawn.
The Cozio defence. Black firmly supports his queenside knight and e-pawn while blocking in his dark-squared bishop. Nowadays this is rare at most levels.
A thematic move in most Ruy Lopez variations: Black puts the question to White's bishop.
White aims to create a powerful pawn centre using his c-pawn to control d4 before moving his d-pawn there.
White now has a very powerful Classical pawn centre and is preparing to thrust forwards and gain space with d5!
Black tries to regain space with a queenside expansion forcing White's bishop back.
Black chases White's bishop away while weakening his pawn structure.
Preparing to fianchetto the bishop on g7 where it will control the long h8-diagonal.
Black has to prevent 11.Nxf7 which forks Black's queen and rook. However this walks into another fork 11.d5! which wins minor piece for pawn.
White pushes a centre pawn into enemy territory blocking Black's position and forking his bishop and knight. Black now clearly has a very blocked up position.
Although it loses material this move is preferable to playing Bc8 which blocks up Black's position even more wastes moves and leads to this bishop being trapped.
A nice sacrifice which Black has to accept risking the loss of his rook otherwise. This exposes Black's king.
White is going on the attack. His pieces are swarming in to attack Black's exposed king.

White uses every single one of his well-developed pieces. From having a blocked cumbersome position Black now has a vulnerable position that has been cracked open like an egg. This neat skewer winning queen for bishop completely seals the game for White.
Preparing Qc7#.
Black's king is forced into the corner ready for a checkmate.
Checkmate is still forced as we see in the next two moves.
A classic queen and knight checkmating position.

Checking up on my opponent's other games I found he was quite the devotee of the Bishop's Opening. There's nothing especially wrong with it but it's a long time since Weaver Adams was optimistically claiming it as a forced win for White.
Unusual. I figured I might as well take the pawn as go straight into the Two Knights' Defence by transposition (3. ... Nc6).

With his dark bishop free and having castled White seems to have a couple of tempi for his pawn sacrifice. On the other hand a pawn is a pawn and I was expecting 5. d4 leading into Canal's Attack after 5. ... exd4; 6. Re1 d5; 7. Bxd5 Qxd5; 8. Nc3 when White recovers all his material with a good game (though the position's quite defensible for Black).

And this for my money is a poor move. In the Two Knights' proper it comes a couple of moves earlier while White still has his e-pawn. Then Black is more or less obliged to give up a pawn with 4. ... d5; 5. exd5 Na5; as the recapture 5. ... Nxd5 invites the dangerous "Fried Liver" attack with 6. Nxf7 Kxf7; 7. Qf3  Ke6. But now I can play 6. ... d5 safely and White's extra tempi vanish.

There was the threat to drive the White knight back and pin it with 9. ... h6 and 10. ... Bg4 which would be troublesome as the White KB is offside and can't break the pin. But the position is surprisingly dangerous now Black has caught up in development and has a strong centre.
White is reluctant to give the two Bishops but there is a worse threat.
After 11. Nf3 Nxf3; 12. gxf3 Bh3 Black has a dangerous attack on the White King but the text loses a piece.
And not 12. gxh3 Nf3 ! winning the Queen. But no matter the twists and turns Black keeps his extra piece.
Alternatively 13. Bxd7 Nxd7 and Black keeps both his centre pawns as the threat of 14. ...Nxc2 prevents 13. Nxd5. But the text allows Black to pick up two more pawns.
A piece and two pawns ahead Black need only play steadily - but with the White Knight far removed from his King White has to fear a mating attack.
Black was happy to exchange both because of his existing material superiority and the prospect of gaining further time by kicking the White pieces around some more.
Making a loophole for the King and relieving most of the threats associated with the back rank. But Black now gains even more time to improve his position.
Taking advantage of White's last which leaves the Rook on c5 quite shut in. There is only one safe square.

White's Rook now has an egress along the rank but no squares available to it as yet. Meanwhile Black now has a pair of connected passed pawns which would win the game out of hand if the pieces were traded off.

Hi everyone!  This game was even right up to the early middlegame when a tactical shot won me a pawn.  Somehow I managed to increase my lead in material until a king move on black's part finally managed to wrap things up.  You would think that with the queens off the board you are safe from Old Matey - well just remember a rook is also mating material and it is quite possible to crawl into what is known as a mating net.  This game provides an example of this.

5. ......... a6 - a Naijdorf Sicilian - this move is to prepare a later b5 and to stop any knight incursions on that square although it has not been unknown for the white player to sacrifice a knight on b5 for the pawn.
9. Qd2 - standard development and paving the way for queenside castling.

15. Nd7 - quite a bit has happened in the space of a few moves firstly I castle queenside after an exchange of pawns and then comes a plethora of exchanges leading to the current position.  I now need to develop Frere Leblanc to get my king rook into play.
17. Rd1 - rook centralised as planned - puts pressure on one of the enemy knights.  Black is about to make his first mistake........
17......... h6? - this loses a pawn becase of the loose knight on d7 - I also bust up black's kingside pawns into the bargain!
20. Ne4 - a useful outpost for my knight now that the f pawn is pinned.
21. Rxb7 - black's previous move Nc6? just drops another pawn.
22. Bxa6 - and another black pawn bites the dust - I now have 3 queenside passers!

25. ......... Kg5 - not fatal but inaccurate play could result in a snap mate on the side if black is not careful.  I have spent the last few moves controlling all the open files to consolidate my position.  Hopefully I will find a way to finish this game somehow.  Ah what is this I think I have another target here the e pawn!
27. Nd5  - this knight move becomes pivotal to what is to come later.

28. Rxe5 - now black is 4 pawns down!  However while he still has his rook and a couple of minor pieces against my own on the board I still have work to do.  Who would have thought though that this game is going to terminate in just four more moves?
29. Kb1 - Henry decides to back up the a pawn and sidestep any potential pins on the c file.
30. ........... Kg4?? - see my next note.

31. Be2  - here I announced mate in 3 and black resigned.  Dmaestro has already given me the correct answer in a pm here but to any other reader can you spot the checkmate.  Answers on a postcard.  Cheers.  Joanne.
